  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>A DCF relies entirely on mathematical projections. Here are factors that could drive value differently than projected.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Unprecedented grid modernization:</strong> If government and utility spending heavily accelerates for renewables grid upgrades, orders and FCF growth might exceed our 15% rate.</li>
    <li><strong>Rapid AI power demand:</strong> Soaring power needs for AI data centers may massively boost demand for GE Vernova's gas turbines and grid solutions.</li>
    <li><strong>Stronger margin accretion:</strong> Operational efficiencies post-spin-off could result in cash flow growth greatly outpacing revenue growth.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Wind segment volatility:</strong> Offshore wind is notoriously cyclical and capital intensive. Supply chain issues or project cancellations can decimate free cash flow.</li>
    <li><strong>Execution risks:</strong> Being a newly spun-out independent company, operational missteps in large, complex infrastructure projects could erode expected margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Slowing energy transition:</strong> Changes in political or regulatory landscapes around renewable incentives could slow grid spending.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a P/E multiple?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Multiples depend entirely on market sentiment and peer comparisons, which can be irrationally exuberant. A DCF grounds valuation in the cash the business actually produces over time.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is a 10% discount rate appropriate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Given a risk-free rate (10Y Treasury) of 4.18% and adding an equity risk premium of ~5.5-6%, 10% is the standard hurdle rate for evaluating high-quality industrial and energy equipment companies.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is historical FCF negative before 2023?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">GE Vernova was part of the larger General Electric structure and was burdened by struggling power and wind businesses. A significant restructuring and spin-off allowed them to reset operations, which has resulted in the sudden, rapid margin recovery seen since 2024.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is a purely educational valuation framework. It shows the implied value based on cash flows. Always do your own research and evaluate your own risk.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

